T1  - Equilibrium models displaying endogenous fluctuations and chaos: A survey
AU  - Boldrin, Michele
AU  - Woodford, Michael
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 25
IS  - 2
SP  - 189
EP  - 222
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/03/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(90)90013-T
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030439329090013T
AB  - This paper surveys current developments in dynamic general equilibrium theory concerned with conditions under which endogenous fluctuations are possible. Existing contributions are divided into two classes: the larger one consists of models with a unique perfect-foresight equilibrium, while the second includes models where equilibrium is indeterminate and the set of equilibria involving endogenous fluctuations includes ‘sunspots equilibria’. While the two classes of models involve oscillations of different natures and with different policy implications, we show that both are consistent with optimizing behavior and competitive equilibrium.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Nonmonetary effects of financial crises: Lessons from the great depression in Canada
AU  - Haubrich, Joseph G.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 25
IS  - 2
SP  - 223
EP  - 252
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/03/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(90)90014-U
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030439329090014U
AB  - This paper empirically examines the nonmonetary effects of financial crises. It exploits the special nature of the Great Depression in Canada to test propositions linking financial structure and aggregate economic activity. Canada's large domestic debt and shrinking banking system had little impact on the course of the Depression. In comparison with results for the United States, this implicates bank failures as a prime factor in the real effects of financial crises.
